request.description:
StartFragment

### postGeoObject

- verb: POST
- endPoint: /ManageGeoObject/postGeoObject
- returns: UID
    

#### Parameters

- GeoObject: It's the information that will determine which type will be placed on the tak maps including his icon. Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries. Since 1.7 you can also use nicknames for the geo objects.
- longitude: OPTIONAL the angular distance of the geoobject from the meridian of the greenwich, UK expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g -76.107.7998). Remember to set the display of your TAK in decimal coordinates, where _West 77.08_ is equal to '-77.08' in the API.
- latitude: OPTIONAL the angular distance of the geoobject from the earths equator expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g 43.855682).
- how: the way in which this geo information has been acquired. Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries.
- attitude: OPTIONAL the kind of expected behavior of the GeoObject (e.g friendly, hostile, unknown). Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries.
- name: a string to ID the GeoObject on a map.
- bearing: OPTIONAL since 1.7, the direction expressed in degrees (1-360). Default: 0.
- distance: OPTIONAL since 1.7, the distance in meters from the Lat/long or address.
- timeout: OPTIONAL the length, expressed in seconds until the point will stale out. Default is 300 seconds or 5 minutes.
- uid: optional input parameter, need to be an Unique Id for this element, if not present will be server generated, if sent ATAK will try to update an existing geoObject. Use `putGeoObject` instead
- address: OPTIONAL address of destination. If sent will try to solve the exact geolocation of the destination. Possible valid examples are:
    - Big Arkansas River Park, Wichita, KS, USA
    - Wichita, KS, USA
    - Big Arkansas River Park, Wichita
    - and so on.

request.description:
StartFragment

retrieve in a array all geoObjects in a given radius. It uses JSON variables, not the json body

- verb: GET
- endPoint: /ManageGeoObject/getGeoObject
    

#### Parameters

NOTE: these should be provided in the form of url encoded variables. \* radius: radius in meters where geoObjects, default(100). \* longitude: longitude from which radius is calculated, default(0). \* latitude: latitude from which radius is calculated, default(0). \* attitude: (optional) the attitude which will be filtered, default(any). See list of supported attitudes above.

##### EXAMPLE VARIABLES

``` json
{
  "longitude": -77.02385,
  "latitude": 38.989,
  "attitude": "Hostile",
  "radius": 500
}

 ```

`URL http://[IP]:[PORT]/ManageGeoObject/getGeoObject?longitude=-77.0104&latitude=38.889&radius=5000`

EndFragment

StartFragment

#### putGeoObject

update an existing geoObject coordinates (can also update other features)

- verb: PUT
- endPoint: /ManageGeoObject/putGeoObject
- returns: UID
    

#### Parameters

- **REQUIRED** uid: optional input parameter, need to be an Unique Id for this element, if not present will be server generated, if sent ATAK will try to update an existing geoObject. Use `putGeoObject` instead.
- **REQUIRED** GeoObject: It's the information that will determine which type will be placed on the tak maps including his icon. Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries.
- **REQUIRED** longitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the meridian of the greenwich, UK expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g -76.107.7998). Remember to set the display of your TAK in decimal coordinates, where _West 77.08_ is equal to '-77.08' in the API.
- **REQUIRED** latitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the earths equator expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g 43.855682).
- **REQUIRED** attitude: the kind of expected behavior of the GeoObject (e.g friendly, hostile, unknown). Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries.
- how: the way in which this geo information has been acquired. Please see API documentation for a list of valid entries.
- name: a string to ID the GeoObject on a map.
- bearing: since 1.7, the direction expressed in degrees (1-360).
- distance: since 1.7, the distance in meters from the Lat/long.
- timeout: the length, expressed in seconds until the point will stale out. Default is 300 seconds or 5 minutes.
    

EndFragment

This HTTP GET request is used to retrieve a list of active checklists. The request URL is `{{basessl}}/Marti/api/excheck/checklist/active` and it includes a query parameter `clientUid` with the value `e7f71100-dbbe-4d93-b5b8-1037935f6ee6`.

The response to this request is a XML document containing a list of active checklists. Each checklist has the following details:

- `name`: The name of the checklist.
- `uid`: The unique identifier of the checklist.
- `description`: The description of the checklist.
- `startTime`: The start time of the checklist.
- `templateName`: The name of the template used for the checklist.
- `creatorUid`: The unique identifier of the checklist creator.
- `creatorCallsign`: The callsign of the checklist creator.
- `missions`: The missions associated with the checklist.
    

Please note that the response may contain multiple checklists, each represented by a element.

You can use this endpoint to retrieve the active checklists and their details for further processing or display.

request.description:
This HTTP GET request is used to retrieve a list of ExCheck templates for missions. The request is sent to the endpoint `{{basessl}}/Marti/api/missions/ExCheckTemplates`.

The last execution of this request returned a response with a status code of 200. The response body contains an array of objects with the following properties:

- `version`: The version of the ExCheck template.
- `type`: The type of the ExCheck template.
- `data`: An array of objects representing the ExCheck templates. Each object has the following properties:
    - `name`: The name of the ExCheck template.
    - `tool`: The tool associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `keywords`: An array of keywords associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `creatorUid`: The unique identifier of the creator of the ExCheck template.
    - `createTime`: The creation time of the ExCheck template.
    - `groups`: An array of groups associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `externalData`: An array of external data associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `feeds`: An array of feeds associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `mapLayers`: An array of map layers associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `inviteOnly`: A boolean value indicating if the ExCheck template is invite-only.
    - `expiration`: The expiration time of the ExCheck template.
    - `uids`: An array of unique identifiers associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `contents`: An array of objects representing the contents of the ExCheck template. Each object has the following properties:
        - `data`: An object representing the data of the content. It has the following properties:
            - `filename`: The filename of the content.
            - `keywords`: An array of keywords associated with the content.
            - `mimeType`: The MIME type of the content.
            - `name`: The name of the content.
            - `submissionTime`: The submission time of the content.
            - `submitter`: The submitter of the content.
            - `uid`: The unique identifier of the content.
            - `hash`: The hash of the content.
            - `size`: The size of the content.
            - `tool`: The tool associated with the content.
            - `expiration`: The expiration time of the content.
        - `timestamp`: The timestamp of the content.
        - `creatorUid`: The unique identifier of the creator of the content.
    - `passwordProtected`: A boolean value indicating if the ExCheck template is password protected.
- `nodeId`: The node identifier.
    

Please note that the specific values of the properties in the response may vary.

This HTTP GET request is used to retrieve a list of ExCheck templates for missions. The request is sent to the endpoint `{{basessl}}/Marti/api/missions/ExCheckTemplates`.

The last execution of this request returned a response with a status code of 200. The response body contains an array of objects with the following properties:

- `version`: The version of the ExCheck template.
- `type`: The type of the ExCheck template.
- `data`: An array of objects representing the ExCheck templates. Each object has the following properties:
    - `name`: The name of the ExCheck template.
    - `tool`: The tool associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `keywords`: An array of keywords associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `creatorUid`: The unique identifier of the creator of the ExCheck template.
    - `createTime`: The creation time of the ExCheck template.
    - `groups`: An array of groups associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `externalData`: An array of external data associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `feeds`: An array of feeds associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `mapLayers`: An array of map layers associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `inviteOnly`: A boolean value indicating if the ExCheck template is invite-only.
    - `expiration`: The expiration time of the ExCheck template.
    - `uids`: An array of unique identifiers associated with the ExCheck template.
    - `contents`: An array of objects representing the contents of the ExCheck template. Each object has the following properties:
        - `data`: An object representing the data of the content. It has the following properties:
            - `filename`: The filename of the content.
            - `keywords`: An array of keywords associated with the content.

        - `timestamp`: The timestamp of the content.

request.description:
This API endpoint is used to retrieve the status of a checklist. It makes an HTTP GET request to the specified URL with the checklist UID and token as query parameters.

The response for this request will be an HTML document containing the checklist information. The document will include the checklist name, progress, and a table displaying the pending tasks. The progress is represented as a fraction, with the numerator indicating the number of completed tasks and the denominator indicating the total number of tasks.

if we've got a token, find the corresponding missionChange and checklistTask, and recreate the checklist at the time of the change

Here are some examples of the response for this request:

Example 1:

```
Checklist : MI IV Weaponization
Progress : 3/12
The following task is now Pending:
| Name           | Description    | Due Relative DTG |
|----------------|----------------|------------------|
| Install ...    | Install ...    |                  |

 ```

Example 2:

```
Checklist : MI IV Weaponization
Progress : 3/12

 ```

Please note that the response will be in HTML format, and the content will be rendered as per the HTML tags used in the response.

To make this request, you need to provide the checklist UID and token as query parameters in the URL.

Example Request:

```
GET {{basessl}}/Marti/api/excheck/checklist/:checklistuid/status?token=0ad61d1512cd73e1e18e0f3337ebdf5719b2862e6d1b4af12395ea41addf487a

 ```

in TAK server this is handled here:

[https://github.com/TAK-Product-Center/Server/blob/8cb3c65aa40d3fe6b02af78eab5d2fc4094d7d20/src/takserver-plugins/src/main/java/com/bbn/marti/sync/model/MissionChange.java#L387](https://github.com/TAK-Product-Center/Server/blob/8cb3c65aa40d3fe6b02af78eab5d2fc4094d7d20/src/takserver-plugins/src/main/java/com/bbn/marti/sync/model/MissionChange.java#L387)

request.description:
This HTTP PUT request is used to subscribe a user to a mission in the Marti API. The mission UID is specified in the URL path parameter ":missionuid", and the user UID is provided as a query parameter "uid". The user wants to "Add documentation" for this request.

### Request

- Method: PUT
- URL: {{basehttp}}/Marti/api/missions/:missionuid/subscription?uid=ANDROID-351811095448994
    

### Response

The last execution of this request returned a response with the following details:

- Status: 201 (Created)
- Body:
    
    ``` json
      {
        "data": {
            "clientUid": "",
            "createTime": "",
            "role": {
                "permissions": [""],
                "type": ""
            },
            "token": "",
            "username": ""
        },
        "nodeId": "",
        "type": "",
        "version": ""
      }
    
     ```
    

Please note that the response body contains empty values for several properties. These properties may hold specific values in actual responses.

Invite a certain type to the mission.

the enum type includes:

clientUid, callsign, username, group, team

defined in:

takserver-core/takserver-war/src/main/java/com/bbn/marti/sync/model/MissionInvitation.java
invite a list of usrs, unclear how the contacts array is structured

request.description:
the expiration is set to be a Unix timestamp which is the number of seconds since January 1, 1970 (also known as the Unix epoch).

The long number 1678115580 represents a Unix timestamp for 2023-02-04 17:06:20

StartFragment

1702560322 would be Date and time (GMT): Thursday, December 14, 2023 1:25:22 PM

EndFragment

Add a log entry to the server.

- content : The text of the log entry
- creatorUid : Client UID
- entryUid : UID of associated CoT track
- missionNames : Missions to associate with this log entry
- text of the log entry, not a server-side timestamp)
    

The response is a reflection of the incoming request - with the significant addition of the **id**, which is a pseudo-random 128-bit identifier assigned by the server at entry creation time, and "servertime" - the server-side timestamp at creation time

mission.

item.description:
The Data Sync / Mission API provides the capability in TAK Server for clients, such as ATAK,  
to share collections of information which are tracked as part of missions. Once a mission has  
been created by a client, it immediately becomes available to other clients (Assuming they have the plugin).

A substantial portion the API and related functions have been developed in order to provide clients with the ability to add and remove relevant mission content, determine what changes to missions have been done by other clients, and then request updates for only what each client requires. In this way, each client can always maintain a consistent local view of missions and their contents, which conserving resources such as local storage and network bandwidth.

There are several types of content that can be associated with a mission:

- **CoT tracks**: CoT tracks are referenced by their UID, so that any information that can be  
    represented in a mission. Once CoT UIDs have been added to a mission, the server can then  
    provide the client with the latest CoT event associated with each UID
- **enterprise sync resources**: Files can be uploaded to TAK Server through the Enterprise Sync API. The adds generality such that any type of file that is useful from a client perspective can be added to a mission.  
    Common files types include GRGs, images, and KML (Keyhole markup language) files. These  
    resources are referenced by calculating a deterministic hash for each file, based on the binary  
    contents of the file. Once the association has been made between a mission and a file, the  
    file contents of the mission can be searched by parameters including time interval and  
    geographic location.
- **Check Lists:** requires the ExChecks plugin installed. Allow the collaborative execution of a series of tasks
- **mission logs**: Mission Logs are a series of free-form text entries that can be viewed individually or as a complete log.
    

In addition to CoT tracks and files, each mission can also contain a "Mission Log" (also referred to as a "Recce Log"). Mission logs are composed of individual log entries, which clients post to the server. Once a log entry has been added, it immediately becomes available as part of the mission log, in a similar fashion to enterprise sync resources and CoT tracks. CoT UIDs and file resources can also be associated with individual log entries,  
just as they can be associated with missions. Log entries may also be updated and deleted.  
Similarly, tracks and files can also be removed from the mission. Every change to the state of a mission, including the creation or deletion of the mission itself, is tracked by TAK Server. Based on this information, the server can generate a change log detailing each change to the mission over time. This log can be filtered based on an arbitrary time interval.  
Clients may subscribe to one or more missions. Once a client has subscribed to a mission, the server will send it a CoT message informing the client of each change. Based on this notification, the client can then request a change log for an appropriate time range.

request.description:
#### postRoute

- verb: POST
    
- endpoint: /ManageRoute/postRoute
    
- returns: uid
    

#### parameters

- timeout: OPTIONAL the length, expressed in seconds until the point will stale out. Default is 300 seconds or 5 minutes.
    
- address: OPTIONAL address of destination. If sent will try to solve the exact geolocation of the destination. Possible valid examples are:
    
    - Big Arkansas River Park, Wichita, KS, USA
        
    - Wichita, KS, USA
        
    - Big Arkansas River Park, Wichita
        
    - and so on.
        
- method: OPTIONAL the method we plan to use for the route (Driving, Flying, Walking, Swimming, Watercraft). currently not used and set to Driving in the client.
    
- longitudeDest: OPTIONAL if address is not sent.
    
- latitudeDest: OPTIONAL if address is not sent.
    
- uid: OPTIONAL server generated Unique Id of this element. it will update the existing element.
    
- routeName:OPTIONAL the name of the route.
    
- endName: OPTIONAL the name of the destination (end point on the route).
    
- startName: OPTIONAL the name of the start (start point of the route).
    
- uid: OPTIONALserver generated Unique Id of this element. it will update an existing route.
    
- longitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the meridian of the greenwich, UK expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g -76.107.7998). Remember to set the display of your TAK in decimal coordinates, where _West 77.08_ is equal to '-77.08' in the API.
    
- latitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the earths equator expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g 43.855682).

- verb: POST
- endpoint: /Sensor/postDrone
- returns: DRONE_UID, SPI_UID
    

#### parameters

- timeout: OPTIONAL the length, expressed in seconds until the point will stale out. Default is 300 seconds or 5 minutes.
- name: the name of the drone, will become also the name of the video stream.
- Range: the range of view of the sensor in meters.
- Bearing: the direction in which the sensor is aimed in degrees.
- FieldOfView: the field of view of the drone in degrees.
- VideoURLUID: the address of the video stream. DJI drones only support RTMP protocol. You need to have FreeTAKHub Video service active to see a stream.
- longitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the meridian of the greenwich, UK expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g -76.107.7998). Remember to set the display of your TAK in decimal coordinates, where _West 77.08_ is equal to '-77.08' in the API.
- latitude: the angular distance of the geoobject from the earths equator expressed in positive or negative float. (e.g 43.855682).
- uid: OPTIONAL input parameter, needed to update existing drone COT.
- SPIName: the name of the Sensor Point of Interest the UAS is currently aiming to. currently will NOT work in a update message (when you send the UID).
- SPILongitude: longitude of target. currently will NOT work in a update message (when you send the UID).
- SPILatitude: latitude of target. currently will NOT work in a update message (when you send the UID).
    

EndFragment

request.description:
send a Datapackage to all the connected clients.

takes the DP ID as a parameter

- PrimaryKey: primary key of DataPackage to be modified
- Name: optional new name of DataPackage if not set name will not be changed
- Keywords: optional new keywords of DataPackage if not set keywords will not be changed
- Privacy: optional new privacy of DataPackage if not set privacy will not be changed must be 1(Private) or 0(Public)

#### postVideoStream

- verb: POST
    
- endpoint: /ManageVideoStream/postVideoStream
    
- returns: uid
    

#### parameters

- "streamAddress": the IP of the video server.
    
- "streamPort": the port the video server respond to.
    
- "streamPath": the unique path of the video stream\* "alias": a name for the stream.
    
- "streamProtocol": the type of protocol used (e.g. rtsp, rtmp, raw).
